# MCP servers are the keystone signal: their traffic routes through Anthropic's
# servers, so they bypass any VM network allowlist. A session that cannot fetch
# a live website may still create repos and deploy through MCP.
#
# TWO WAYS IN, ONLY ONE IS VISIBLE:
#   1. config files (.mcp.json, ~/.claude.json)  -> this probe can see them
#   2. harness/connector injection (per-session,  -> INVISIBLE to a subprocess
#      configured on the Anthropic side)
# So the mcp primitive never reports "unavailable", only "available" or
# "unknown". Absent from config is not absent from the session. Verified the
# hard way: a cloud session reported both servers below as unavailable while
# both were live and authenticated.
#
# The detector reports CONFIGURED at most. It never claims authentication, and
# authentication never implies authorization (see mcp.github's remediation).
# The whereami skill confirms both with read-only calls.

Capability mcp.github
  Description GitHub MCP server (repos, PRs, API without direct network)
  Probe mcp github
  Requires An authenticated GitHub session on the Anthropic side
  Remediation Add the GitHub MCP server or enable the connector, then authenticate once from an interactive session. NOTE, authenticated does not mean authorized: in Claude Code cloud the GitHub MCP authenticates as the Claude GitHub App, and a GitHub App installation token CANNOT create a personal repository (POST /user/repos accepts only a user OAuth token or a classic PAT with repo scope), so repo creation returns 403 "Resource not accessible by integration" on a perfectly good network. Create personal repos from a local session, or create them under an org (POST /orgs/{org}/repos works for an App with Administration permission).
  Risk low
  Environments local cloud

Capability mcp.vercel
  Description Vercel MCP server (deploys without direct network)
  Probe mcp vercel
  Requires An authenticated Vercel session on the Anthropic side
  Remediation Add the Vercel MCP server or enable the connector and authenticate it once from an interactive session. Its deploy tool ships a file tree directly, so it needs no git import and no repo; a first deploy to a brand-new project becomes that project's production alias even when a preview target is requested.
  Risk low
  Environments local cloud
